# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

llama.cpp routes chat templates through a dispatcher (`common_chat_try_specialized_template` in `common/chat.cpp`) that pattern-matches the raw Jinja source to select a C++ handler. Handlers for complex formats (tool calls, reasoning) exist for Ministral-3, Kimi K2, Functionary v3.2, etc. Unknown templates fall back to an automatic PEG-parser generator.

The Mistral Instruct v0.3 format (`[INST]/[/INST]` markers, system message prepended to first user turn, `</s>` after assistant turns) currently has no dedicated handler and falls through to the auto-parser. Additionally, Mistral Nemo — which uses the same `[INST]/[/INST]` structure plus a `[TOOL_CALLS][{name, arguments, id}]` tool-call format — also has no dedicated handler.

The new handler covers both formats: v0.3 base (content-only) and Nemo (with tool calls). Detection distinguishes it from the Ministral-3 handler by checking for the **absence** of `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` and `[ARGS]`.

Constraint: **only add new code** — do not modify any existing handler or header file.

---

## Files to Change

| File | Action |
|------|--------|
| `common/chat.cpp` | Add handler function (after line 1517) + detection condition (after line 1688) |
| `tests/test-chat.cpp` | Add new test block (after line 3148) |
| `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja` | Create new file |

---

## Step 1 — Create the Minimal Jinja Template

**File (new):** `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja`

```jinja
{%- if messages[0]["role"] == "system" %}
    {%- set system_message = messages[0]["content"] %}
    {%- set loop_messages = messages[1:] %}
{%- else %}
    {%- set loop_messages = messages %}
{%- endif %}
{{- bos_token }}
{%- for message in loop_messages %}
    {%- if message["role"] == "user" %}
        {%- if loop.first and system_message is defined %}
            {{- "[INST]" + system_message + "\n\n" + message["content"] + "[/INST]" }}
        {%- else %}
            {{- "[INST]" + message["content"] + "[/INST]" }}
        {%- endif %}
    {%- elif message["role"] == "assistant" %}
        {{- message["content"] + eos_token }}
    {%- else %}
        {{- raise_exception("Only user and assistant roles are supported!") }}
    {%- endif %}
{%- endfor %}
```

Intentionally has `[INST]` and `[/INST]` but **not** `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, `[ARGS]`, or `[TOOL_CALLS]`, so the detection condition below fires for it.

---

## Step 2 — Add the Handler Function

**File:** `common/chat.cpp`  
**Anchor:** After the closing `}` of `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` at line 1517, before `namespace workaround {` at line 1519.

Insert between lines 1517 and 1519:

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;
    data.preserved_tokens  = {
        "[TOOL_CALLS]",
    };

    auto has_tools       = inputs.tools.is_array() && !inputs.tools.empty();
    auto include_grammar = has_tools && inputs.tool_choice != COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        if (!has_tools || inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE) {
            include_grammar = false;
            return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
        }

        // Mistral Nemo tool call format:
        //   [TOOL_CALLS][{"name": "func", "arguments": {...}, "id": "123456789"}]
        // The section_start "[TOOL_CALLS][" already includes the opening '[' of the JSON
        // array, so array_wrapped = false (brackets are part of the section markers).
        auto tool_calls = p.standard_json_tools(
            /* section_start     = */ "[TOOL_CALLS][",
            /* section_end       = */ "]",
            /* tools             = */ inputs.tools,
            /* parallel          = */ inputs.parallel_tool_calls,
            /* force             = */ inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_REQUIRED,
            /* name_key          = */ "name",
            /* args_key          = */ "arguments",
            /* array_wrapped     = */ false,
            /* function_is_key   = */ false,
            /* call_id_key       = */ "id",
            /* gen_call_id_key   = */ "",
            /* parameters_order  = */ {"name", "arguments", "id"});

        // Content runs up to the optional [TOOL_CALLS] section.
        // p.content(p.until("[TOOL_CALLS]")) matches empty when tool_choice == REQUIRED
        // and the model outputs a tool call immediately.
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) +
               p.content(p.until("[TOOL_CALLS]")) +
               tool_calls + p.end();
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    if (include_grammar) {
        data.grammar_lazy = has_tools && inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_AUTO;
        data.grammar = build_grammar([&](const common_grammar_builder & builder) {
            foreach_function(inputs.tools, [&](const json & tool) {
                const auto & function = tool.at("function");
                auto         schema   = function.at("parameters");
                builder.resolve_refs(schema);
            });
            parser.build_grammar(builder, data.grammar_lazy);
        });
        data.grammar_triggers = {
            { COMMON_GRAMMAR_TRIGGER_TYPE_WORD, "[TOOL_CALLS]" }
        };
    }

    return data;
}
```

**Key design notes:**
- `standard_json_tools` is called with `section_start = "[TOOL_CALLS]["` — the `[` that opens the JSON array is embedded in the prefix (same pattern as the Cohere test in `test-chat-auto-parser.cpp`).
- `parameters_order = {"name", "arguments", "id"}` matches Nemo's Jinja which serializes `function|tojson` (giving `name` + `arguments`) then appends `"id"` last.
- `p.content(p.until("[TOOL_CALLS]"))` gracefully handles REQUIRED tool choice — if the model outputs `[TOOL_CALLS]` immediately, `until` matches the empty string and the content node is empty.
- No `p.end()` in the content-only path (matches pattern in other content-only handlers).

---

## Step 3 — Add the Detection Condition

**File:** `common/chat.cpp`  
**Anchor:** After the GigaChat block closing `}` at line 1688, before `return std::nullopt;` at line 1690.

Insert between lines 1688 and 1690:

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 / Mistral Nemo - [INST]...[/INST] markers without [SYSTEM_PROMPT] or [ARGS].
    // Covers both the basic v0.3 content-only format and the Nemo variant that adds
    // [TOOL_CALLS][{"name":…,"arguments":…,"id":…}] for tool calls.
    // Ministral-3 (has [SYSTEM_PROMPT]+[ARGS]) and Mistral Small 3.2/Devstral (have [SYSTEM_PROMPT])
    // are already handled above and excluded by the [SYSTEM_PROMPT] absence check.
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[/INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[ARGS]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3/Nemo\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

**Why this placement and these conditions:**
- Placed last in the dispatcher (just before `return std::nullopt`) so all more-specific checks have already run.
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absent: Ministral-3, Devstral, and Mistral Small 3.2 all include `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` in their templates → excluded.
- `[ARGS]` absent: extra guard that excludes any remaining `[ARGS]`-based template not yet caught by the Ministral-3 check.
- The existing Nemo template (`mistralai-Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407.jinja`) has `[INST]`/`[/INST]` and lacks both `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` and `[ARGS]`, so it is now routed here instead of the auto-parser.

---

## Step 4 — Add Test Cases

**File:** `tests/test-chat.cpp`  
**Anchor:** After the closing `}` of the Nemo test block at line 3148, before `{` opening the functionary-medium-v3.1 block at line 3149.

Insert between lines 3148 and 3149:

```cpp
    // mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja (basic [INST]/[/INST], no tool calls)
    {
        auto tst = peg_tester("models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3.jinja", detailed_debug);
        tst.test("Hello, world!\nWhat's up?").expect(message_assist).expect_reconstruction().run();
    }
```

The two existing Nemo test cases at lines 3139–3148 — plain-content and `[TOOL_CALLS]` with `expect_reconstruction()` — now automatically exercise the new handler (since Nemo's template is routed to it by the detection condition) and serve as tool-call regression tests.

---

## Verification

```bash
# Build the test binary
cmake -B build -DLLAMA_BUILD_TESTS=ON
cmake --build build --parallel --target test-chat

# Run all chat tests (includes both new and existing Nemo tests)
./build/bin/test-chat

# Run only the v0.3 template (fast iteration on new template)
./build/bin/test-chat --template Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3

# Run only the Nemo template (regression check — now via new handler)
./build/bin/test-chat --template Mistral-Nemo

# Force reconstruction tests on every template (broad regression)
./build/bin/test-chat --force-reconstruction-test
```

**Expected outcomes:**
1. New v0.3 test: parses `"Hello, world!\nWhat's up?"` → `message_assist`; reconstruction round-trip passes.
2. Existing Nemo content test: still passes (content-only path unchanged).
3. Existing Nemo tool-call test: `[TOOL_CALLS][{…,"id":"123456789"}]` → `message_assist_call_id`; reconstruction passes (Nemo Jinja re-emits the `[TOOL_CALLS]` block including `</s>`; since reconstruction only requires the output starts with `prompt + input`, the trailing `</s>` is acceptable per lines 1263–1265 of the test).

